:INFO
Raising Meat Rabbits in a Suburban Yard
Rabbits are one of the most efficient meat animals for small spaces. They are quiet, odor-controlled with proper management, and convert feed to meat faster than any common livestock. A colony of 3 does and 1 buck produces meaningful protein year-round.

:COUNTER.half
4 Lbs
Average live weight at 8 to 10 weeks for processing
|
:COUNTER.half
6 Weeks
Time from kindle to weaning for a standard litter

:PATH
Set Up Housing
Wire-floor hutches elevated off the ground keep rabbits clean and reduce parasite pressure. Each doe needs her own cage with a nesting box. The buck lives separately. Cover with a roof for weather protection.

:PATH
Feed a Simple Diet
A 16 to 18% protein commercial pellet is the simplest approach. Add grass hay free choice and supplemental greens. Avoid sugary or starchy treats. Fresh water in a bottle or crock must always be available.

:PATH
Manage Breeding
Bring the doe to the buck's cage, never the reverse. Confirm pregnancy by palpating at day 12 to 14. Provide a nesting box with hay at day 28. Kindling occurs around day 31.

:CHECKLIST
Getting Started Checklist
[ ] Check local ordinances for rabbit keeping rules
[ ] Source hutches or build to minimum 30x30 inches per adult
[ ] Purchase or source starter rabbits from a reputable breeder
[ ] Have pellets, hay, and water system ready before rabbits arrive
[ ] Learn humane processing technique before first litter matures
[ ] Set up a simple record card for each doe

:NOTE
New Zealand White and California breeds are the industry standard for meat production. They are docile, fast-growing, and widely available from breeders.
